| 1923 || || Internal fact-checking operations || ''TIME Magazine'', around the time of its first issue, hires Nancy Ford for a role that would	include verifying basic dates, names and facts in completed TIME articles. This would mark the beginning of the magazine's fact-checking operation, which would hire a handful of people, all women.<ref name=time-history-of-fact-checking>{{cite web|url = http://time.com/4858683/fact-checking-history/|title = Here’s How the First Fact-Checkers Were Able to Do Their Jobs Before the Internet|last = Fabry|first = Merrill|date = August 24, 2017|accessdate = April 23, 2018|publisher =  ''TIME Magazine''}}</ref> || United States (but some content covers global topics)
