| 2017 || January || Alleged fake news || On January 3, [[wikipedia:Breitbart News|Breitbart News]] publishes a story with the title "1,000-Man Mob Attack Police, Set Germany’s Oldest Church Alight on New Year’s Eve".<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.breitbart.com/london/2017/01/03/dortmund-mob-attack-police-church-alight/|title = Revealed: 1,000-Man Mob Attack Police, Set Germany’s Oldest Church Alight on New Year’s Eve|last = Hale|first = Virginia|date = January 3, 2017|accessdate = May 23, 2017|publisher = ''[[wikipedia:Breitbart News|Breitbart News]]''}}</ref> The accuracy of the story is contested by a number of outlets including the ''[[wikipedia:Washington Post|Washington Post]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/allahu-akbar-chanting-mob-sets-alight-germanys-oldest-church-shocking-story-if-it-were-true/2017/01/06/30470f58-d36a-11e6-9651-54a0154cf5b3_story.html?utm_term=.c596d8bfc662|title = ‘Allahu akbar’-chanting mob sets alight Germany’s oldest church? Shocking story, if it were true.|last = Faiola|first = Anthony|last2 = Kirchner|first2 = Stephanie|date = January 6, 2017|accessdate = May 23, 2017|publisher = ''[[wikipedia:Washington Post|Washington Post]]''}}</ref> It leads to a renewed interest among German politicians in tackling the "fake news" problem, along with suspicions of interference from Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.mediamatters.org/blog/2017/01/09/germany-investigating-unprecedented-proliferation-fake-news-wake-fabricated-breitbart-story/214965|title = Germany Investigating "Unprecedented Proliferation" Of Fake News In Wake Of Fabricated Breitbart Story|last = Holt|first = Jared|publisher = [[wikipedia:Media Matters for America|Media Matters for America]]|date = January 9, 2017|accessdate = May 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.theverge.com/2017/1/10/14222490/germany-fake-news-breitbart-russia-election|title = Germany investigates fake news after bogus Breitbart story. Officials suspect Russian meddling ahead of parliamentary elections|last = Toor|first = Amar|date = January 10, 2017|accessdate = May 23, 2017|publisher = ''[[wikipedia:The Verge|The Verge]]''}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jan/09/germany-investigating-spread-fake-news-online-russia-election|title =  Germany investigating unprecedented spread of fake news online. Government focus on false reporting comes amid claims that Russia is trying to influence German election later this year|date = January 9, 2017|accessdate = May 23, 2017|publisher = [[wikipedia:Reuters|Reuters]]}}</ref> ''Breitbart News'' continues to defend its coverage and attacks the use of the "fake news" label for its reporting.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.breitbart.com/london/2017/01/08/fake-news-fake-news-media-sow-division-with-dishonest-attack-on-breitbarts-allahu-akbar-church-fire-story/|title = Fake ‘Fake News’: Media Sow Division with Dishonest Attack on Breitbart’s ‘Allahu Akbar’ Church Fire Story|last = Kassam|first = Raheem|date = January 8, 2017|accessdate = May 23, 2017|publisher = ''[[wikipedia:Breitbart News|Breitbart News]]''}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.mediamatters.org/blog/2017/01/09/breitbart-has-literally-unbelievable-response-its-false-german-church-story/214961|title = Breitbart Has A Literally Unbelievable Response To Its False German Church Story|last = Gertz|first = Matt|date = January 9, 2017|accessdate = May 23, 2017|publisher = [[wikipedia:Media Matters for America|Media Matters for America]]}}</ref> || Germany
